Orchestrates one full cage run — prepare → run → teardown — for `ctx-cage`, the sandboxing tool that execs Claude inside `bwrap`. This is the single public entry point (`execute`) that host binaries call after resolving CLI args and tool paths into a `Resolved` struct.

The three phases are split into private submodules (`prepare`, `run`, `teardown`) purely to satisfy a workspace file-length policy; logic and behavior are effectively part of this orchestrator, not independent components. `execute` guarantees teardown always runs, even if `run` fails or the proxy thread/`bwrap` crashes — teardown errors are swallowed (best-effort), while `prepare`/`run` errors propagate as `CageError`.

Critical, easy-to-miss step: before doing anything else, `execute` canonicalizes `target_root` via `canonicalize_target`. This is load-bearing, not cosmetic — `bwrap` binds `target_root` at an identical path inside the cage (per ADR-046) alongside other always-absolute binds (`/cage/bin`, `/opt/cage/rules.md`, `/run/ctx`). A relative `target_root` (e.g. `.` from `ctx-run .`) mixed with those absolute binds causes `bwrap` to create real directories on the host disk at the mount points instead of using the sandboxed root. Any caller constructing `Resolved` must not assume `target_root` needs pre-canonicalization — this function does it unconditionally.

`Resolved` is the sole input contract: target root, task id (names the run dir, exported as `TASK=`), `Mode`, absolute paths to the real `ctx-verify`/`ctx-context`/`ctx-scan` binaries, and `allow_dirty` (default false — billed modes refuse a dirty git tree unless overridden). Billed-mode gating (API key presence, tree cleanliness) happens inside `prepare::prepare_run`, not here.